column2: This term describes how a quantitative variable is divided into equal-width bins, representing the number of values falling into each bin.
This type of graph uses adjacent bars to display the frequency or relative frequency of values in each bin for a quantitative variable.
This term refers to a region in a distribution where there are no values.
This type of display shows quantitative data values in a way that sketches the distribution.
This type of graph represents each case with a dot plotted against a single axis.
To describe this feature of a distribution, one must look for modes, symmetry, skewness, outliers, and gaps.
This term describes the point in a distribution that would summarize the entire distribution with a single number.
This term refers to a numerical summary of how tightly values cluster around the center.
This term refers to a hump or local high point in the shape of a distribution.
This term is used when a distribution has one mode or two modes.
This term describes a distribution that is roughly flat.
A distribution is said to have this characteristic when the two halves on either side of the center look like mirror images.
These are parts of a distribution that trail off on either side.
A distribution is described by this term if it is not symmetric and one tail stretches out farther than the other.
This term describes extreme values that don’t appear to belong with the rest of the data.
This term refers to the middle value of a dataset, where half the data is above and half is below.
This term refers to the difference between the lowest and highest values in a dataset.
This term refers to values that divide data into four parts with equal numbers of data values.
